    "# Chemical Process Monitoring Time-Series Dataset  \n",
    "## Notebook 3: Feature Engineering\n",
    "\n",
    "### Project Context\n",
    "In the previous notebooks, we established that:\n",
    "\n",
    "- the dataset is strongly time-dependent\n",
    "- the process operates under distinct regimes\n",
    "- faults are rare and context-dependent\n",
    "- vibration is a strong fault signal\n",
    "- faults often appear as instability rather than large mean shifts\n",
    "\n",
    "Raw sensor values alone are often not enough for effective fault detection. In industrial time-series problems, predictive performance usually improves when raw measurements are transformed into features that capture:\n",
    "\n",
    "- temporal memory\n",
    "- local instability\n",
    "- deviation from contextual baselines\n",
    "- interactions between variables\n",
    "- recent fault history\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Objectives of This Notebook\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook focuses on engineering model-ready features that help capture early warning signals and system dynamics.\n",
    "\n",
    "Specifically, we will create:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Time-based features**\n",
    "2. **Lag features**\n",
    "3. **Rate-of-change features**\n",
    "4. **Rolling statistical features**\n",
    "5. **Regime-relative deviation features**\n",
    "6. **Interaction features**\n",
    "7. **Fault-history features**\n",
    "8. **Spike / anomaly flags**\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Why Feature Engineering Matters\n",
    "\n",
    "In this dataset, faults are not always obvious from raw values. Instead, they often emerge as:\n",
    "\n",
    "- small deviations from normal ranges\n",
    "- shifts relative to regime baselines\n",
    "- bursts of instability\n",
    "- abnormal short-term movement patterns\n",
    "\n",
    "Feature engineering helps convert these hidden patterns into explicit signals that machine learning models can learn more effectively."
   ]
