    "### Lag Feature Interpretation\n",
    "\n",
    "Lag features introduce historical context by allowing the model to access past values of each variable. This is critical in time-series systems where the current state often depends on recent behavior.\n",
    "\n",
    "We created lag features at:\n",
    "- **1 step** (1 minute ago)\n",
    "- **5 steps** (5 minutes ago)\n",
    "- **10 steps** (10 minutes ago)\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Key Observations\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Temporal dependency captured**  \n",
    "  Process variables such as temperature, pressure, and conversion rate evolve gradually rather than instantaneously. Lag features allow the model to learn these temporal dependencies.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Early fault signal detection**  \n",
    "  Many faults do not occur abruptly but develop over time. Lagged variables help capture:\n",
    "  - gradual drifts  \n",
    "  - instability buildup  \n",
    "  - pre-fault behavior patterns  \n",
    "\n",
    "- **Reactor-specific history preserved**  \n",
    "  By applying lag within each `reactor_id`, we ensure:\n",
    "  - no data leakage between reactors  \n",
    "  - accurate tracking of each unit’s operational history  \n",
    "\n",
    "- **Expected missing values (NaNs)**  \n",
    "  The first few rows for each reactor contain `NaN` values because there is no prior history available.  \n",
    "  This is expected and must be handled during modeling (e.g., dropping or imputing).\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Stronger predictive power**  \n",
    "  Lag features significantly enhance model performance by transforming the dataset from purely static observations into a **dynamic, time-aware representation**.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Conclusion\n",
    "\n",
    "Lag features are essential for capturing short-term memory in the system, enabling the model to detect evolving patterns and improving its ability to predict faults before they fully develop."
   ]
